    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are speaking to the core debate in constitutional theory between strict originalism and modern pragmatism, but the answer lies in whether the text itself grants the court or the legislature the power to declare rights \"extinguished.\" Many scholars argue that if the Constitution contains a \"shall not be infringed\" clause, any later amendment—like the 18th—cannot logically erase a previously established right through ordinary political majority rules. Therefore, the validity of Originalism often depends on the premise that specific Founding-era rights survive implicitly or that the \"infringement\" clause only protects them from new laws, not erasure. Since the Founders themselves debated whether rights were created by nature alone or by Constitution alone, declaring one approach the \"only legitimate\" way often requires taking a stance that wasn't explicitly settled by the Framers themselves.",
